          "body": "2 Kings 1 is the final chapter before Elijah's translation (2:1-12). The Elijah narrative that began with confronting Ahab in 1 Kings 17:1 ends here with confronting Ahab's son. The structure is deliberate: Elijah's ministry begins by announcing drought to Ahab and ends by announcing death to Ahaziah. He bookends the Omri dynasty's apostasy with the same prophetic formula — 'thus says the LORD.' His appearance is unchanged: the hairy garment and leather belt of 1:8 are the same prophet described in 1 Kings 18. He is Elijah to the last. The angel of the LORD who commissioned him in vv. 3-4 and who releases him in v. 15 will in the next chapter send a fiery chariot to take him home. Chapter 1 is thus Elijah's final assignment — a word delivered, soldiers consumed, a king confronted, a prophecy fulfilled — before the whirlwind."
