        "excerpt": "Moab rebelled against Israel after the death of Ahab… So he sent messengers and said to them, 'Go, inquire of Baal-zebub, the god of Ekron, whether I will recover from this sickness.'",
        "body": "The chapter opens with two events that belong together: Moab's rebellion and Ahaziah's accident. The narrator places them in sequence to signal a pattern. The death of Ahab in 1 Kings 22:37 removed the last strong Omride, and Moab immediately tested the succession — a political reading of weakness. Ahaziah's fall through the lattice (sevakhah, a wickerwork window designed for ventilation, not load-bearing) in his upper chamber compounds the political crisis with a personal one. He is king of a fractured realm and now a sick man on a bed.\n\nThe moment is the chapter's diagnostic point. What does a king do when confronted with mortality and political collapse? The text records no prayer, no summons of a prophet of YHWH, no consultation of the Torah. Ahaziah sends messengers to Baal-zebub of Ekron — a Philistine oracle city thirty-five miles to the southwest. The choice is not ignorance; it is deliberate. His father Ahab had prophets of YHWH available (1 Kings 22:6) even while persecuting them. Ahaziah simply did not want what YHWH would say.\n\nEkron was a known oracular center in the ancient Near East. The Mesha Stele and Assyrian records confirm Philistine cult sites operated as divination centers accessible to regional kings. Ahaziah's inquiry was politically reasonable by the standards of his world — and theologically treasonous by the standards of the covenant. Deuteronomy 18:10-12 prohibits exactly this kind of divination, and Deuteronomy 13:1-4 identifies consulting foreign oracles as the test of where one's loyalty truly lies.\n\nThe narrator's economy is pointed: in one verse the sin is complete. There is no deliberation, no competing impulse toward YHWH, no hesitation. The Omride apostasy, which had been building through Ahab's entire reign, has now become instinctive in his son. The reflex of the apostate king is to go anywhere except to the God of Israel.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Darash* (to inquire, vv.2, 3, 6, 16) is the covenant vocabulary for seeking a divine oracle — used of seeking YHWH throughout the Psalms and prophets (Psalm 34:4; Isaiah 55:6; Amos 5:4). Its redirection to Baal-zebub is not a neutral act; it is *darash* performed in the wrong direction. *Chalah* (became ill, v.2) is the same verb used of Ahab's fatal wound in 1 Kings 22:34-35 — another lexical connection binding father and son."
